content:
Use Dataflow Editor, a point-and-click interface, to build your dataflow logic from scratch. Add transformations to determine what source data to use, how to transform that data, and which datasets to load the results into.

Dataflow Editor displays the dataflow you’re editing.

The canvas shows individual nodes in your dataflow and links between them. If you can’t find a node, enter its name in the search box. The node palette has buttons for each type of node. Click one to add it to the canvas.

To create a dataflow from scratch, click Create Dataflow. To edit an existing dataflow, click Edit.

In the node palette, click the node that you want to add. For example, to extract data from a Salesforce object, click sfdcDigest node. Enter a name for the node and its attributes.

Click Create. The new node appears on the canvas. You can drag it to where you want or use your scroll wheel to zoom in and out.

In the node palette, click the next node you want to add. Click augment node to combine data from two sources. Select the fields that will be used for matching records.

Click Create. The new node appears on the canvas with lines showing the input of data from source nodes.

When you finish editing, click Update Dataflow to update the definition file with your changes.

CRM Analytics validates your dataflow to ensure all required attribute values are provided. Correct errors before trying again. After CRM Analytics validates the dataflow, it saves the new version and creates newly defined datasets.

Plan the Dataflow
Consider what data to make available for queries, where to extract the data from, and whether you must transform the extracted data.

A transformation refers to the manipulation of data. You can add transformations to a dataflow to extract data from Salesforce objects or datasets, transform datasets that contain Salesforce or external data, and register datasets.

When editing a dataflow node, consider changes may impact downstream nodes.

You can configure the dataflow by adding transformations directly to the dataflow definition file.
title: Designing Complex Datasets with Salesforce Dataflow Editor
